2.
    a.
        Chemical
    b.
        Burning natural gas is power dense; it can provide energy local to the site of usage so there is no loss from transmission (e.g. in portable stoves or taxis). In addition, burning natural gas can be done in any season at any point in time, and can easily adapt to demand. In contrast, energy generated from the movement of water waves may fluctuate with weather or with season, so power storage may be required, and expensive equipment must be used to extract power from the movement of water waves which must be installed in the sea, which also adds to maintenance costs and to cost of installation. In contrast, the equipment needed to harness power of natural gas locally (in portable stoves or taxis) may not be very expensive.

        However, burning natural gas is not renewable, whereas harnessing the movement of water waves is renewable. In addition, burning natural gas releases greenhouse gases such as carbon dioxide, which contribute to global warming, whereas harnessing the movement of water waves does not. Burning natural gas may also release smog etc which may cause pollution, which harnessing the movement of water waves does not cause. However, structures in the sea which use the movement of water waves to generate electricity may cause damage to aquatic ecosystems as they may interrupt the movement of aquatic organisms such as fish or the communication of whales as they may cause noise pollution underwater.
