8.
    a.
        i.
            It could be possible if star C is further away from Earth than star A, since apparent luminosity decreases the further away from the source the observer is.
        ii?
            Star D is in the supernova stage of its evolution, since it has a much higher mass than our sun (17.1 times), which allows it to go supernova in the first place, but also because it has a very low absolute magnitude, which indicates that it is very bright, which is a symptom of a supernova as stars release a lot of energy and are very bright in the supernova stage.
    b.
        A main sequence star evolves into a supernova when it is more massive than our sun. When such a star reaches the end of main sequence life, it becomes a red supergiant. Then, as it runs even more out of fuel, the star is no longer able to provide enough outward pressure to maintain its size and resist gravity, causing the star to collapse, which triggers the fusion of heavier elements, which causes an explosion, supernova, ejecting much of the matter of the star. Afterwards, the star can become a neutron star or a black hole.
    c.
        i.
            ((7.78 * (10^{(-7)}) - 7.774 * (10^{(-7)})))/(7.78 * (10^{(-7)})) * 3 * 10^8 = 231362.467866 m/s ~= 231000 m/s = 2.31 * 10^5 m/s
        ii.
            Red-shifted light detected from supernovas in nearby galaxies having shorter wavelengths than the red-shifted light detected from supernovas in galaxies further away suggests that the galaxies further away are travelling at a higher speed, as velocity of galaxy = change in wavelength/reference velocity * speed of light; reference velocity and speed of light can be treated as constant, so the velocity of the galaxy must be higher if the change in wavelength is higher, and since red shift lengthens the wavelength, the fact that further galaxies have longer wavelengths compared to shorter wavelengths in closer galaxies implies further galaxies are faster than nearer galaxies. This supports the big bang theory, as if all matter and galaxies began at the same point, it would be necessary that matter would arrange itself in a manner that matter close by would have similar velocities; i.e. that, from earth's perspective, the difference in velocity between it and closer matter/galaxies would be lower than the difference in velocity between it and further matter/galaxies, which is what was shown before (further galaxies have a higher relative velocity than closer galaxies), so the big bang theory is supported.